{"id":11440,"date":"2018-10-18T17:57:07","date_gmt":"2018-10-18T12:27:07","guid":{"rendered":"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/?p=11440"},"modified":"2018-10-26T11:51:01","modified_gmt":"2018-10-26T06:21:01","slug":"ram-v-sutar","status":"publish","type":"post","link":"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/ram-v-sutar\/","title":{"rendered":"Ram V Sutar (Sculptor) Wiki, Age, Wife, Family, Biography, Facts &amp; More"},"content":{"rendered":"<p style=\"text-align: center\"><img decoding=\"async\" class=\"aligncenter size-full wp-image-11442\" src=\"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/10\/Ram-V-Sutar.jpg\" alt=\"Ram V Sutar\" width=\"480\" height=\"547\" srcset=\"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/10\/Ram-V-Sutar.jpg 480w, https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/10\/Ram-V-Sutar-263x300.jpg 263w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 480px) 100vw, 480px\" \/><\/p>\n<p><strong>Ram Vanji Sutar<\/strong> is a famous Indian Sculptor who has sculpted more than 50 monumental sculptures around the World. He has been active in this field Since the 1950s. He has gained popularity for his sculptures of Mahatma Gandhi. He will be remembered forever for his dedication to the art and architecture.<\/p>\n<div id=\"ez-toc-container\" class=\"ez-toc-v2_0_62 counter-hierarchy ez-toc-counter ez-toc-custom ez-toc-container-direction\">\n<p class=\"ez-toc-title\">Contents<\/p>\n<label for=\"ez-toc-cssicon-toggle-item-65bce1e6dcf88\" class=\"ez-toc-cssicon-toggle-label\"><span class=\"\"><span class=\"eztoc-hide\" style=\"display:none;\">Toggle<\/span><span class=\"ez-toc-icon-toggle-span\"><svg style=\"fill: #000000;color:#000000\" xmlns=\"http:\/\/www.w3.org\/2000\/svg\" class=\"list-377408\" width=\"20px\" height=\"20px\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" fill=\"none\"><path d=\"M6 6H4v2h2V6zm14 0H8v2h12V6zM4 11h2v2H4v-2zm16 0H8v2h12v-2zM4 16h2v2H4v-2zm16 0H8v2h12v-2z\" fill=\"currentColor\"><\/path><\/svg><svg style=\"fill: #000000;color:#000000\" class=\"arrow-unsorted-368013\" xmlns=\"http:\/\/www.w3.org\/2000\/svg\" width=\"10px\" height=\"10px\" viewBox=\"0 0 24 24\" version=\"1.2\" baseProfile=\"tiny\"><path d=\"M18.2 9.3l-6.2-6.3-6.2 6.3c-.2.2-.3.4-.3.7s.1.5.3.7c.2.2.4.3.7.3h11c.3 0 .5-.1.7-.3.2-.2.3-.5.3-.7s-.1-.5-.3-.7zM5.8 14.7l6.2 6.3 6.2-6.3c.2-.2.3-.5.3-.7s-.1-.5-.3-.7c-.2-.2-.4-.3-.7-.3h-11c-.3 0-.5.1-.7.3-.2.2-.3.5-.3.7s.1.5.3.7z\"\/><\/svg><\/span><\/span><\/label><input type=\"checkbox\"  id=\"ez-toc-cssicon-toggle-item-65bce1e6dcf88\"  aria-label=\"Toggle\" \/><nav><ul class='ez-toc-list ez-toc-list-level-1 ' ><li class='ez-toc-page-1 ez-toc-heading-level-2'><a class=\"ez-toc-link ez-toc-heading-1\" href=\"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/ram-v-sutar\/#BiographyWiki\" title=\"Biography\/Wiki\">Biography\/Wiki<\/a><\/li><li class='ez-toc-page-1 ez-toc-heading-level-2'><a class=\"ez-toc-link ez-toc-heading-2\" href=\"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/ram-v-sutar\/#Family\" title=\"Family\">Family<\/a><\/li><li class='ez-toc-page-1 ez-toc-heading-level-2'><a class=\"ez-toc-link ez-toc-heading-3\" href=\"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/ram-v-sutar\/#Career\" title=\"Career\">Career<\/a><\/li><li class='ez-toc-page-1 ez-toc-heading-level-2'><a class=\"ez-toc-link ez-toc-heading-4\" href=\"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/ram-v-sutar\/#Awards\" title=\"Awards\">Awards<\/a><\/li><li class='ez-toc-page-1 ez-toc-heading-level-2'><a class=\"ez-toc-link ez-toc-heading-5\" href=\"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/ram-v-sutar\/#Interesting_Facts\" title=\"Interesting Facts\">Interesting Facts<\/a><\/li><\/ul><\/nav><\/div>\n<h2><span class=\"ez-toc-section\" id=\"BiographyWiki\"><\/span><span style=\"color: #800080\">Biography\/Wiki<\/span><span class=\"ez-toc-section-end\"><\/span><\/h2>\n<p>Ram V. Sutar was born on <strong>19 February 1925 (Age 93; as in 2018)<\/strong>\u00a0in a poor <strong>Vishwakarma family<\/strong> in Gondur village of <strong>Dhule district<\/strong> of Maharashtra. His father Vanji Hansraj was also a <strong>carpenter<\/strong> and <strong>sculptor<\/strong>. As a child, he developed his interest in this profession. In his childhood, he was motivated towards art by\u00a0<strong>Shriram Krishna Joshi<\/strong>, whom he considers his mentor. It was Shriram Krishna Joshi who encouraged him to join\u00a0<strong>Sir J.J. School of Art<\/strong>\u00a0in Bombay (Now, Mumbai). In the last year of his study, he topped his class and won the prestigious <strong>Mayo Gold medal<\/strong> for modelling\u00a0(Sculpture).<\/p>\n<div id=\"attachment_11446\" style=\"width: 510px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img decoding=\"async\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-11446\" class=\"size-full wp-image-11446\" src=\"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/10\/Ram-V-Sutar-making-sculptures.jpg\" alt=\"Ram V Sutar making sculptures\" width=\"500\" height=\"320\" srcset=\"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/10\/Ram-V-Sutar-making-sculptures.jpg 500w, https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/10\/Ram-V-Sutar-making-sculptures-300x192.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 500px) 100vw, 500px\" \/><p id=\"caption-attachment-11446\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Ram V Sutar making sculptures<\/p><\/div>\n<h2><span class=\"ez-toc-section\" id=\"Family\"><\/span><span style=\"color: #800080\">Family<\/span><span class=\"ez-toc-section-end\"><\/span><\/h2>\n<p>He was born to\u00a0Vanji <strong>Hansraj<\/strong> and\u00a0<strong>Sitabai<\/strong>. He was the only son of his parents.<\/p>\n<p>In 1952, he married to <strong>Pramila<\/strong>. He has a son, <strong>Anil Sutar<\/strong>\u00a0who is also a professional sculptor.<\/p>\n<div id=\"attachment_11447\" style=\"width: 650px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img decoding=\"async\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-11447\" class=\"size-full wp-image-11447\" src=\"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/10\/Ram-Sutar-left-with-his-son-Anil-right.jpg\" alt=\"Ram Sutar (left) with his son Anil (right)\" width=\"640\" height=\"480\" srcset=\"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/10\/Ram-Sutar-left-with-his-son-Anil-right.jpg 640w, https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/10\/Ram-Sutar-left-with-his-son-Anil-right-300x225.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 640px) 100vw, 640px\" \/><p id=\"caption-attachment-11447\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Ram Sutar (left) with his son Anil (right)<\/p><\/div>\n<h2><span class=\"ez-toc-section\" id=\"Career\"><\/span><span style=\"color: #800080\">Career<\/span><span class=\"ez-toc-section-end\"><\/span><\/h2>\n<p>From 1954 to 1958, he worked at <strong>Ajanta and Ellora caves<\/strong> in Aurangabad district of Maharashtra. He restored the old statues of the caves. In 1958, Sutar became a\u00a0<b>Technical Assistant\u00a0<\/b>in the\u00a0<b>Ministry of Information &amp; Broadcasting<\/b>\u00a0in\u00a0<b>New Delhi<\/b>\u00a0for preparing various types of model for the five years plan. In order to become an Independent professional sculptor, he<strong> left his government job<\/strong> in 1959.<\/p>\n<div class=\"flex-video flex-video-youtube\"><iframe width=\"1060\" height=\"596\" src=\"https:\/\/www.youtube.com\/embed\/eSVr5f2xVto?feature=oembed\" frameborder=\"0\" allow=\"autoplay; encrypted-media\" allowfullscreen><\/iframe><\/div>\n<p>His first noticeable\u00a0work was the 45-feet <strong>Goddess Chambal sculpture<\/strong> (Also known as Chambal Monument) at the Gandhi Sagar Dam in Madhya Pradesh, India.<\/p>\n<div id=\"attachment_11449\" style=\"width: 330px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img decoding=\"async\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-11449\" class=\"size-full wp-image-11449\" src=\"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/10\/The-statue-of-Chambal-Mother-was-sculpted-by-Ram-V-Sutar.jpg\" alt=\"The statue of Chambal Mother was sculpted by Ram V Sutar\" width=\"320\" height=\"462\" srcset=\"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/10\/The-statue-of-Chambal-Mother-was-sculpted-by-Ram-V-Sutar.jpg 320w, https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/10\/The-statue-of-Chambal-Mother-was-sculpted-by-Ram-V-Sutar-208x300.jpg 208w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 320px) 100vw, 320px\" \/><p id=\"caption-attachment-11449\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">The statue of Chambal Mother was sculpted by Ram V Sutar<\/p><\/div>\n<p>The most well-known work of him is the <strong>bust of Mahatma Gandhi,<\/strong> which is recognised Worldwide. The government of India presented it to Italy, France, Germany, Russia, England, Argentina, etc. He has also sculpted a 17-feet high sculpture of Mahatma Gandhi in Meditation pose, which has been installed near Parliament House, Delhi and Gandhi Nagar, Gujarat.<\/p>\n<div id=\"attachment_11450\" style=\"width: 670px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img decoding=\"async\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-11450\" class=\"size-full wp-image-11450\" src=\"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/10\/Prime-Minister-Narendra-Modi-unveiling-the-bust-of-Mahatma-Gandhi-on-13-April-2015.jpg\" alt=\"Prime Minister Narendra Modi unveiling the bust of Mahatma Gandhi on 13 April 2015 in Hannover, Germany\" width=\"660\" height=\"422\" srcset=\"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/10\/Prime-Minister-Narendra-Modi-unveiling-the-bust-of-Mahatma-Gandhi-on-13-April-2015.jpg 660w, https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/10\/Prime-Minister-Narendra-Modi-unveiling-the-bust-of-Mahatma-Gandhi-on-13-April-2015-300x192.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 660px) 100vw, 660px\" \/><p id=\"caption-attachment-11450\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Prime Minister Narendra Modi unveiled the bust of Mahatma Gandhi on 13 April 2015 in Hannover, Germany<\/p><\/div>\n<p>His another notable work is the 21-feet high\u00a0Equestrian <strong>statue of\u00a0Maharaja Ranjit Singh<\/strong> which was installed at Amritsar in Punjab.<\/p>\n<div id=\"attachment_11452\" style=\"width: 560px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img decoding=\"async\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-11452\" class=\"size-full wp-image-11452\" src=\"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/10\/Maharaja-Ranjit-Singh-statue-in-Amrisar-was-sculpted-by-Ram-V-Sutar.jpg\" alt=\"Maharaja Ranjit Singh statue in Amritsar was sculpted by Ram V Sutar\" width=\"550\" height=\"413\" srcset=\"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/10\/Maharaja-Ranjit-Singh-statue-in-Amrisar-was-sculpted-by-Ram-V-Sutar.jpg 550w, https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/10\/Maharaja-Ranjit-Singh-statue-in-Amrisar-was-sculpted-by-Ram-V-Sutar-300x225.jpg 300w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 550px) 100vw, 550px\" \/><p id=\"caption-attachment-11452\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Maharaja Ranjit Singh statue in Amritsar was sculpted by Ram V Sutar<\/p><\/div>\n<p>He also designed the <strong>Statue of Unity<\/strong>, an iconic <strong>182-meter tall<\/strong> landmark statue (tallest in the world) dedicated to Sardar Patel, which is situated near Narmada Dam, Vadodara in Gujarat, India.<img decoding=\"async\" class=\"size-full wp-image-11453\" src=\"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/10\/Statue-of-Unity-was-sculpted-by-Ram-V-Sutar.jpg\" alt=\"Statue of Unity was designed by Ram V Sutar\" width=\"601\" height=\"623\" srcset=\"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/10\/Statue-of-Unity-was-sculpted-by-Ram-V-Sutar.jpg 601w, https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/10\/Statue-of-Unity-was-sculpted-by-Ram-V-Sutar-289x300.jpg 289w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 601px) 100vw, 601px\" \/><\/p>\n<p>Statue of Unity was designed by Ram V. Sutar<\/p>\n<h2><span class=\"ez-toc-section\" id=\"Awards\"><\/span><span style=\"color: #800080\">Awards<\/span><span class=\"ez-toc-section-end\"><\/span><\/h2>\n<p>In 1999, Sutar was awarded <strong>Padma Shri<\/strong> by the Government of India, and in 2016, he was honoured with <strong>Padma Bhushan<\/strong> Award.<\/p>\n<div id=\"attachment_11454\" style=\"width: 490px\" class=\"wp-caption alignnone\"><img decoding=\"async\" aria-describedby=\"caption-attachment-11454\" class=\"size-full wp-image-11454\" src=\"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/10\/Ram-V-Sutar-receiving-Padma-Bhushan-in-2016.jpg\" alt=\"Ram V Sutar receiving Padma Bhushan in 2016\" width=\"480\" height=\"595\" srcset=\"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/10\/Ram-V-Sutar-receiving-Padma-Bhushan-in-2016.jpg 480w, https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-content\/uploads\/2018\/10\/Ram-V-Sutar-receiving-Padma-Bhushan-in-2016-242x300.jpg 242w\" sizes=\"(max-width: 480px) 100vw, 480px\" \/><p id=\"caption-attachment-11454\" class=\"wp-caption-text\">Ram V. Sutar receiving Padma Bhushan in 2016<\/p><\/div>\n<h2><span class=\"ez-toc-section\" id=\"Interesting_Facts\"><\/span><span style=\"color: #800080\">Interesting Facts<\/span><span class=\"ez-toc-section-end\"><\/span><\/h2>\n<ul>\n<li>In his childhood, he was a\u00a0carpenter too. He used to assist his father in his carpentry.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<ul>\n<li>As a kid, he once had the privilege to see\u00a0<strong>Mahatma Gandhi<\/strong>.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<ul>\n<li>PM Narendra Modi inaugurated the <strong>Statue of Unity<\/strong>, the statue of Iron Man of India, <strong>Sardar Vallabhbhai Patel<\/strong>. It took Ram V. Sutar almost three years to complete the Statue of Unity. The statue is worth more than $33 million and made up of <strong>bronze<\/strong>.<\/li>\n<\/ul>\n<div class=\"489bcfb86580b123547338c91db0eff2\" data-index=\"3\" style=\"float: none; margin:3px 0 3px 0; text-align:center;\">\n<ins class=\"adsbygoogle\"\r\n     style=\"display:block\"\r\n     data-ad-format=\"autorelaxed\"\r\n     data-ad-client=\"ca-pub-6769524711517462\"\r\n     data-ad-slot=\"2473600074\"><\/ins>\n<\/div>\n\n<div style=\"font-size: 0px; height: 0px; line-height: 0px; margin: 0; padding: 0; clear: both;\"><\/div>","protected":false},"excerpt":{"rendered":"<p>Ram Vanji Sutar is a famous Indian Sculptor who has sculpted more than 50 monumental sculptures around the World. He has been active in this field Since the 1950s. He has gained popularity for his sculptures of Mahatma Gandhi. He will be remembered forever for his dedication to the art and architecture. Biography\/Wiki Ram V. Sutar was born on 19 February 1925 (Age 93; as in 2018)\u00a0in a poor Vishwakarma family in Gondur village of Dhule district of Maharashtra. His father Vanji Hansraj was also a carpenter and sculptor. As a child, he developed his interest in this profession. In <\/p>\n","protected":false},"author":18,"featured_media":11442,"comment_status":"open","ping_status":"closed","sticky":false,"template":"","format":"standard","meta":{"footnotes":""},"categories":[2],"tags":[],"_links":{"self":[{"href":"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/11440"}],"collection":[{"href":"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts"}],"about":[{"href":"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/types\/post"}],"author":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/users\/18"}],"replies":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/comments?post=11440"}],"version-history":[{"count":12,"href":"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/11440\/revisions"}],"predecessor-version":[{"id":11576,"href":"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/posts\/11440\/revisions\/11576"}],"wp:featuredmedia":[{"embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/media\/11442"}],"wp:attachment":[{"href":"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/media?parent=11440"}],"wp:term":[{"taxonomy":"category","embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/categories?post=11440"},{"taxonomy":"post_tag","embeddable":true,"href":"https:\/\/wikibio.in\/wp-json\/wp\/v2\/tags?post=11440"}],"curies":[{"name":"wp","href":"https:\/\/api.w.org\/{rel}","templated":true}]}}